"""
MKT Context Commentary — Proverbs chapters 1–3
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-1-3.py
Context focus:
- Proverbs 1–9 as the theological framework for the sentence-collections of chs. 10–31
- ANE parallels: Egyptian Instruction genre (Amenemope, Ptahhotep, Any), Mesopotamian wisdom
- The "my son" address as the international wisdom pedagogy standard
- Lady Wisdom (chs. 1, 8, 9) and the personification of divine order
- Ch2 conditional structure as covenant-treaty parallel (if-then blessing)
- Ch3:3 ḥesed-wĕʾemet as the Sinai covenant-character terms (Exod 34:6-7)
- Ch3:18 tree of life as Eden-motif restoration
- Ch3:19-20 wisdom-and-creation as the backdrop for 8:22-31
"""

import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

new_data = {
    "1": {
        "2": "<p>The prologue (vv2&#8211;6) establishes Proverbs&#8217; educational purpose through a chain of infinitives. This structural form has direct parallels in Egyptian wisdom literature: the Instruction of Ptahhotep and the Instruction of Amenemope both open with purpose-statements explaining what the student will gain. Proverbs participates in a pan-ANE tradition of organized moral instruction aimed at forming capable people for court, commerce, and family life, while giving that tradition its distinctively Yahwistic theological ground in v7.</p>",
        "3": "<p>&#8220;Training in wise conduct&#8221; (<i>haśkêl</i>) and the trio of &#8220;righteousness, justice, and integrity&#8221; place Proverbs within the sphere of covenant ethics. This ethical triad appears in Deuteronomy and the prophets as the content of covenant faithfulness (Deut&#160;16:18&#8211;20; Amos&#160;5:24; Mic&#160;6:8). Proverbs does not separate practical wisdom from covenant morality; wisdom without this ethical grounding is mere shrewdness in the service of self-interest.</p>",
        "4": "<p>&#8220;The naive (<i>pᵉtāyîm</i>)&#8221; who can still be formed is a key social category in the wisdom tradition. Egyptian instruction literature also targets the young man entering professional life, typically the son of a scribe or official. Israel democratizes this: the teacher in Proverbs addresses &#8220;my son&#8221; not necessarily a court apprentice but any young person in the covenant community who has not yet hardened into either wisdom or folly. The window of formability is the wisdom tradition&#8217;s educational opportunity.</p>",
        "5": "<p>The expansion of the audience from the naive to the already-wise in v5 reflects the cumulative nature of wisdom. The Egyptian Instructions of Any and Amenemope similarly address those who already have some formation and need refinement. Wisdom is not a one-time acquisition but a lifelong spiral: the wise grow wiser through continued exposure to wise teaching. The word for &#8220;skill in guidance&#8221; (<i>taḥbulôt</i>) is used of naval steering — wisdom is the skill of navigating, not a destination one arrives at.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&#8220;To understand a proverb and its meaning, the words of the wise and their enigmas&#8221; — the hermeneutical goal of the collection. The reader must learn not just to receive proverbs but to work with them, to see through the surface to the deeper application. This is the difference between the student and the wise person: the student learns proverbs; the wise person understands how to use them across varying situations. Analogical thinking — the capacity to see when a proverb applies and when it does not — is the mark of mature wisdom (cf. 26:7&#8211;9, where the same proverb in different hands produces different results).</p>",
        "7": "<p>&#8220;The fear of the LORD is the beginning of knowledge&#8221; is the theological thesis of the entire book, stated here at the opening and repeated at 9:10 (&#8220;the beginning of wisdom&#8221;) and 15:33. Parallel formulations in Job 28:28 (&#8220;the fear of the Lord, that is wisdom&#8221;) and Ps&#160;111:10 confirm that this is not a distinctive of Proverbs but a consensus of the wisdom tradition. The &#8220;fear of the LORD&#8221; is the foundational covenant disposition — the posture of the person who lives within YHWH&#8217;s world as his creature and covenant partner. Without this orientation, all the practical skills of wisdom are miscalibrated from the start.</p>",
        "8": "<p>The &#8220;my son&#8221; (<i>bᵉnî</i>) address that begins the main instructional body of chs.&#160;1&#8211;9 is the standard address of the wisdom instruction genre across the ancient world. The Instruction of Amenemope consistently addresses the student as &#8220;my son&#8221; or &#8220;my beloved son.&#8221; The Instructions of Any address &#8220;my son.&#8221; In Israel the domestic setting — father and mother teaching the son — gives this instruction a covenantal family character: the Deuteronomic command to teach children &#8220;when you sit in your house&#8221; (Deut&#160;6:7) is here given its practical wisdom content.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The jewelry imagery — garland on the head, chain around the neck — places wisdom in the register of honor and social distinction. In the ancient world, jewelry marked rank and station; to be adorned with wisdom&#8217;s garland is to be publicly identified as someone of distinction. The same image appears in Egyptian wisdom: the Instruction of Amenemope promises that the student who heeds instruction will &#8220;be adorned&#8221; among men. Social honor is wisdom&#8217;s natural fruit within the covenant community.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The first formal temptation speech (vv10&#8211;14) is a rhetorical device unique to Proverbs among wisdom texts: the teacher gives full voice to the temptation so the student can recognize its form. This practice — dramatizing the seduction to immunize against it — is pedagogically sophisticated. The student who has heard the gang&#8217;s speech in the safety of the teaching context will recognize it when encountered in the street. The form of the temptation (belonging, solidarity, shared wealth) is timeless and culturally universal.</p>",
        "11": "<p>The violent ambush scenario (vv11&#8211;14) likely reflects actual social conditions in ancient Israelite urban life, where criminal gangs preyed on travelers and the naive. The covenant law&#8217;s repeated concern with &#8220;innocent blood&#8221; (Deut&#160;19:10&#8211;13; 21:1&#8211;9; Ps&#160;106:38) provides the legal background: shedding innocent blood defiles the land and brings covenant judgment. The gang that solicits the young man is not merely breaking social norms but violating the most fundamental covenant protections.</p>",
        "12": "<p>The Sheol/grave imagery used by the sinners (v12) draws on the ancient Israelite understanding of the underworld as an insatiable, personified realm that devours the dead (cf. Isa&#160;5:14; Hab&#160;2:5). The sinners&#8217; boast that they will swallow victims &#8220;alive like Sheol&#8221; identifies their violence with the power of death itself — they present themselves as embodiments of mortality. The irony (vv18&#8211;19) is that by identifying with Sheol&#8217;s appetite, they invite Sheol&#8217;s attention onto themselves.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The &#8220;treasure&#8221; (<i>hôn yāqār</i>) and &#8220;loot&#8221; (<i>šālāl</i>) appeal reflects the reality that banditry and gang violence were viable economic strategies in the ancient world for those outside the structures of legitimate work and patronage. The wisdom tradition consistently presents the legitimate labor of agriculture, craftsmanship, and trade as the honorable path to wealth. The criminal shortcut is both morally condemned and practically self-defeating — it costs the practitioners their lives (v19).</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Throw in your lot (<i>gôrālᵉkā</i>) with us&#8221; — the lot-casting image places the decision to join the gang in the language of the communal rituals of Israel, where lots determined everything from inheritance to the appointment of the Day of Atonement&#8217;s goats (Lev&#160;16:8&#8211;10; Josh&#160;18:6&#8211;10). The irony is stark: the lot that should orient one toward the covenant community and its God is here redirected toward a criminal fraternity.</p>",
        "15": "<p>The father&#8217;s counter-instruction uses the path-and-way metaphor that dominates Proverbs&#8217; moral geography. Two-ways teaching — the way of wisdom vs. the way of folly, the way of life vs. the way of death — is the organizing moral framework of Deut&#160;30:15&#8211;20 (&#8220;I set before you today life and death, blessing and curse&#8221;) and finds its most developed wisdom expression in Ps&#160;1:1&#8211;6. Proverbs does not present moral life as a neutral landscape but as a set of diverging roads with incommensurable destinations.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The &#8220;feet that run to evil&#8221; language connects to the prophetic literature: Isa&#160;59:7 and Rom&#160;3:15 both quote this motif (perhaps echoing Isa&#160;59) in the context of universal human sinfulness. The observation that the wicked are eager for violence — they run, they rush — highlights the energy that evil can generate in those committed to it. Wisdom is not always the path of least resistance; it requires the deliberate slowing-down of those impulses that run naturally toward harm.</p>",
        "17": "<p>The bird-and-net observation (v17) is a debated interpretive crux. If it means &#8220;even a bird avoids a visible trap — these men are stupider than birds,&#8221; then Proverbs is using the world of nature to mock the sinners&#8217; blindness to consequences. Nature-observation as a source of moral instruction is characteristic of wisdom literature (cf. Prov&#160;6:6&#8211;8 ant; 30:24&#8211;31 four small things; Job 12:7&#8211;9). The created order teaches; those who refuse to learn from it are fools in the most literal sense.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The reversal of vv18&#8211;19 — the ambushers ambush themselves — is the retributive pattern central to the wisdom tradition&#8217;s theology of consequences. Psalm&#160;7:15&#8211;16 states the principle: &#8220;he makes a pit, digging it out, and falls into the hole that he has made.&#8221; Psalm&#160;9:15: &#8220;the nations have sunk in the pit that they made; in the net that they hid, their own foot has been caught.&#8221; Proverbs applies this cosmic principle to the specific case of criminal violence: the criminal act carries within it the seed of its own punishment.</p>",
        "19": "<p>The summary verse on greedy gain (<i>bōṣēaʿ bāṣa&#x2BF;</i>) closes the first instruction unit. The tradition of condemning predatory economic gain runs from Exod&#160;18:21 (Jethro&#8217;s advice to appoint leaders who &#8220;hate unjust gain&#8221;) through Jer&#160;6:13 (&#8220;from least to greatest, all are greedy for gain&#8221;) to Ezek&#160;22:27 (princes like wolves tearing prey for unjust gain). Proverbs&#8217; wisdom insight is that the gain is purchased at the cost of the gainer&#8217;s own life — it is not a net gain at all.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The figure of personified Wisdom (<i>Ḥokmôt</i>) speaking in public (vv20&#8211;33) is one of the most theologically significant features of Proverbs&#160;1&#8211;9. This personification appears also in ch8 (Wisdom&#8217;s extended self-speech) and ch9 (Wisdom&#8217;s feast). Scholars have debated whether the figure derives from the Egyptian goddess Ma&#8217;at (truth/order), the Canaanite goddess Asherah, or is an original Israelite theological development. Most likely, the author uses the personification to communicate that wisdom is not merely a human quality but reflects divine reality — God&#8217;s own order built into creation (8:22&#8211;31).</p>",
        "21": "<p>Wisdom calls in the most public spaces — streets, squares, busy intersections, city gates (vv20&#8211;21). This choice of venue is theologically loaded: the city gate was the center of justice (Amos&#160;5:10&#8211;15; Ruth&#160;4:1), the place where elders judged, merchants traded, and political decisions were made. Wisdom is not a private, mystical illumination for the few; she addresses all Israel in the places where civic life is decided. Her competitors (the seductress, the gang) work in secrecy and darkness; Wisdom works in the open.</p>",
        "22": "<p>The three types addressed in v22 — the naive (<i>pᵉtāyîm</i>), the scoffers (<i>lēṣîm</i>), and the fools (<i>kᵉsîlîm</i>) — represent different stages of distance from wisdom. The naive can still be reached; the scoffers are contemptuous but perhaps not yet irreformable; the fools have settled into complacency. The wisdom tradition recognizes that education operates on a spectrum: the same instruction lands differently depending on where the student is in their moral development. The scoffer is uniquely dangerous because active contempt for wisdom is contagious (13:1; 15:12; 22:10).</p>",
        "23": "<p>Wisdom&#8217;s promise to &#8220;pour out my spirit (<i>rûḥî</i>)&#8221; to those who turn at her rebuke (v23) anticipates the prophetic promises of the divine Spirit (Joel&#160;2:28&#8211;29; Ezek&#160;36:27; Isa&#160;44:3). In the wisdom context, the spirit is the generative power of understanding that Wisdom herself embodies; she promises to share the same animating force that makes her who she is. This verse is one of the clearest points where wisdom and prophecy touch: the same God who speaks through the prophets offers understanding through Wisdom&#8217;s call.</p>",
        "24": "<p>Wisdom&#8217;s shift to past tense in v24 (&#8220;I called and you refused&#8221;) introduces the lawsuit (rîb) pattern familiar from the prophets: God/Wisdom presents evidence of prior invitation rejected (cf. Isa&#160;65:1&#8211;2; 66:4; Jer&#160;7:25&#8211;26; Zeph&#160;1:4&#8211;6). The wisdom lawsuit is not juridical in the same way as the prophetic covenant lawsuit but uses the same forensic rhetoric: the defendant cannot claim ignorance — the call was public, the invitation was clear, the rejection was deliberate.</p>",
        "25": "<p>The rejection of Wisdom&#8217;s counsel (<i>ʿēṣāh</i>) connects to the prophetic tradition&#8217;s critique of Israel for rejecting divine counsel (Isa&#160;5:24&#8211;25; 30:1&#8211;2; Jer&#160;6:19). The covenant lawsuit form makes the point that refusing wisdom is not merely poor judgment but an act of rebellion against the divine order — the same pattern as Israel&#8217;s refusal to hear the prophets. Proverbs reads the moral life of individuals through the same framework the prophets apply to the history of the nation.</p>",
        "26": "<p>Wisdom&#8217;s laughter at the fool&#8217;s calamity (v26) parallels the laughter of God in Ps&#160;2:4; 37:13; 59:8. These psalms present YHWH&#8217;s sovereign irony — his laughter at those who think their rebellion against him will succeed. Wisdom participates in this divine attribute: her laughter is not cruelty but the measured response of the one who warned clearly and was ignored. The laughter of the wise at folly&#8217;s consequences is a recurring motif (cf. Prov&#160;10:23; Ps&#160;52:6).</p>",
        "27": "<p>The storm imagery for disaster — &#8220;like a storm (<i>sûpāh</i>)&#8221; and &#8220;like a whirlwind (<i>sᵉʿārāh</i>)&#8221; — is the standard prophetic vocabulary for divine judgment (Isa&#160;29:6; Nah&#160;1:3; Jer&#160;23:19; Job&#160;38:1 where God speaks from the whirlwind). The disasters of the fool&#8217;s life are portrayed with the same imagery as divine judgment on nations: the individual moral consequences of rejecting wisdom are read through the same theological lens as the great judgments of sacred history.</p>",
        "28": "<p>The reversal of the call-and-answer pattern in v28 (now they call, but Wisdom will not answer) mirrors the reversal of the Psalms: in Pss&#160;3&#8211;7; 22; 88 the psalmist cries &#8220;how long?&#8221; and wonders if God will answer; the guarantee of divine response to the righteous (34:17&#8211;18; 50:15) has its dark counterpart in the silence of God toward the wicked (Ps&#160;50:21&#8211;22; Mic&#160;3:4; Jer&#160;11:11). The timing of seeking matters: the window of repentance has a closing.</p>",
        "29": "<p>The characterization of the fools&#8217; failure as &#8220;hating knowledge and not choosing to fear the LORD&#8221; frames the issue as one of will and covenant relationship rather than intellectual capacity. This is precisely the prophetic diagnosis of Israel&#8217;s unfaithfulness (Hos&#160;4:1&#8211;6: &#8220;there is no knowledge of God in the land... my people are destroyed for lack of knowledge — because you have rejected knowledge&#8221;). The failure to fear YHWH is not ignorance of information but rejection of covenant relationship.</p>",
        "30": "<p>The description of the fools as those who &#8220;wanted none of my advice (<i>lōʾ-ʾābû lᵉ&#x2BF;ᵉṣātî</i>)&#8221; uses the word <i>ʿēṣāh</i> (counsel, purpose) for wisdom&#8217;s instruction. In the wisdom tradition, divine counsel is the plan that stands (19:21; 21:30), the instruction that shapes a well-ordered life. The refusal of wisdom&#8217;s counsel is equivalent to rejecting the very structure of reality — and reality, in the form of consequences, eventually imposes itself regardless.</p>",
        "31": "<p>&#8220;They will eat the fruit of their own path&#8221; expresses the organic moral causality that runs through the wisdom tradition. Galatians 6:7&#8211;8 (&#8220;whatever a man sows, that he will also reap&#8221;) draws on this tradition. Jeremiah 2:19 states the same principle: &#8220;your evil will chastise you, and your apostasy will reprove you.&#8221; In the biblical moral universe, consequences are not arbitrary punishments imposed from outside but the natural harvest of the actions sown. The fool eats what the fool planted.</p>",
        "32": "<p>&#8220;The waywardness (<i>mᵉšûbāh</i>) of the naive will kill them, and the complacency (<i>šalwāh</i>) of fools will be their ruin.&#8221; The word <i>mᵉšûbāh</i> (turning away, apostasy) is the prophetic word for Israel&#8217;s unfaithfulness (Jer&#160;2:19; 3:6&#8211;22; 14:7; Hos&#160;11:7; 14:4). Proverbs uses it for the individual moral trajectory: the naive person&#8217;s drift from wisdom is the same structural pattern as Israel&#8217;s apostasy from YHWH. The individual and national dimensions of the same spiritual failure are described by the same vocabulary.</p>",
        "33": "<p>&#8220;Whoever listens to me will live in security (<i>yiškon-beṭaḥ</i>)&#8221; closes Wisdom&#8217;s speech with the covenant promise. The dwelling in security is precisely the land-promise of Deuteronomy (Deut&#160;12:10; Lev&#160;26:5&#8211;6; Jer&#160;23:6), where YHWH promises his people will &#8220;dwell in safety.&#8221; Wisdom&#8217;s promise to the individual is the same as the covenant&#8217;s promise to the nation: the fruit of faithfulness is peace and security in the place of dwelling. The Instruction of Amenemope ends similarly: the man who follows wisdom&#8217;s teaching will find quiet and peace.</p>"
    },
    "2": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 2 is a single extended conditional sentence in Hebrew — the longest in the book — with a rhetorical structure analogous to the covenant treaties of the ancient Near East: stipulations (vv1&#8211;4) → promises (vv5&#8211;11) → protection from specific enemies (vv12&#8211;19) → covenant goal (vv20&#8211;22). This treaty-echoing structure is not accidental: wisdom instruction is to the individual what the covenant is to the nation. The same &#8220;if... then&#8221; structure appears in the blessings and curses of Deut&#160;28.</p>",
        "2": "<p>The double action of &#8220;turning the ear toward wisdom and directing the heart toward understanding&#8221; reflects the biblical anthropology in which authentic reception involves both attention (ear) and will (heart, <i>lēb</i>). Deuteronomy&#8217;s &#8220;Hear, O Israel&#8221; (<i>šemaʿ</i>) is not merely intellectual hearing but whole-person orientation toward the divine word. Proverbs applies the same framework to wisdom: genuine wisdom-reception is not passive but an active reorientation of the whole person toward what wisdom is offering.</p>",
        "3": "<p>The imperative to &#8220;call out for discernment&#8221; (v3) places wisdom-seeking in the category of prayer. The same verb <i>qārāʾ</i> (to call, to cry out) is used of prayer to YHWH throughout the Psalms (Ps&#160;3:4; 4:3; 17:6; 50:15; 91:15). Proverbs presents the pursuit of wisdom as having a quasi-prayerful character: the seeker who cries aloud for understanding is not just studying but petitioning. The response to that cry is the wisdom that comes from the LORD&#8217;s mouth (v6).</p>",
        "4": "<p>The silver-and-treasure similes for wisdom-seeking (v4) draw on the economic life of the ancient world where silver was mined and treasures were buried in hoards. Archaeological discoveries from Israel&#8217;s Iron Age frequently reveal buried coin hoards and valuables — the image is not merely metaphorical but drawn from lived experience. The effort required — digging (<i>ḥāpar</i>) like a miner — is the experiential analogue of the mental and moral effort that genuine wisdom-formation requires.</p>",
        "5": "<p>&#8220;Fear of the LORD&#8221; and &#8220;knowledge of God&#8221; as the goal of wisdom-seeking (v5) place Proverbs&#8217; practical instruction within the frame of covenant relationship. Hosea&#8217;s critique of Israel (Hos&#160;4:1&#8211;6) centers precisely on the absence of &#8220;knowledge of God&#8221; (<i>daʿat ʾĕlōhîm</i>) and &#8220;steadfast love.&#8221; The wisdom tradition and the prophetic tradition share the diagnosis: the foundational problem of human life is not lack of information but broken covenant relationship with the God who made and ordered all things.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&#8220;The LORD gives wisdom&#8221; (v6) grounds the entire wisdom enterprise in divine grace. This verse stands in tension with the vigorous human seeking of vv1&#8211;4 — but the tension is productive: human seeking and divine giving are both real. The closest analogue is the teaching of James 1:5: &#8220;if any of you lacks wisdom, let him ask God, who gives generously to all without reproach.&#8221; Wisdom is not self-generated through human effort alone but is a divine gift received through the posture of diligent seeking. The two motions are not contradictory but complementary.</p>",
        "7": "<p>&#8220;Stored up (<i>ṣāpan</i>) proven wisdom&#8221; for the upright — the verb &#8220;to store/hide&#8221; reverses the student&#8217;s storing of the teacher&#8217;s words in v1: God stores wisdom for those who seek it, just as they store his words. The image of God as one who has a hidden treasury of wisdom aligns with the wisdom tradition&#8217;s claim that wisdom is hidden in the divine council (Job&#160;28:20&#8211;27; Prov&#160;8:22&#8211;31). The &#8220;shield&#8221; metaphor for divine protection is common in the Psalms (Gen&#160;15:1; Ps&#160;3:3; 28:7), applied here to those whose lives are shaped by integrity.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&#8220;He guards the paths of justice and protects the way of those faithful to him&#8221; applies the divine shepherd/guardian language of Ps&#160;121 and 23 to the wisdom context. YHWH&#8217;s role as guardian of the faithful is a constant in the Psalms (Ps&#160;97:10; 121:3&#8211;8; 145:20). Proverbs localizes this cosmic assurance: the individual who walks the path of wisdom is on the path that God himself actively protects. The wisdom way is not a lonely moral effort but a guarded road.</p>",
        "9": "<p>The result of wisdom-finding is the ability to discern &#8220;what is right, just, and fair — every good way of living&#8221; (v9). This practical ethical discernment corresponds to what Aristotle would later call <i>phronesis</i> (practical wisdom) — the ability to perceive what the right action is in a given situation. The biblical wisdom tradition, however, grounds this discernment not in a trained intellect but in covenant relationship: one understands justice because one knows the God of justice.</p>",
        "10": "<p>&#8220;Wisdom will enter your heart&#8221; (v10) describes the internalization of wisdom — from external teaching to internal disposition. Deuteronomy&#8217;s hope is that the Torah will be &#8220;on your heart&#8221; (Deut&#160;6:6) rather than merely on scrolls or tablets. Jeremiah&#8217;s new covenant promise is that the law will be &#8220;written on their hearts&#8221; (Jer&#160;31:33). Proverbs anticipates this internalization at the level of individual wisdom formation: wisdom moves from the teacher&#8217;s mouth to the student&#8217;s heart as the project of moral education succeeds.</p>",
        "11": "<p>Personified &#8220;discretion&#8221; (<i>mᵉzimmāh</i>) and &#8220;understanding&#8221; (<i>tᵉbûnāh</i>) as guardians mirrors the role of guardian angels in some ANE traditions and the divine protective figures of the Psalms. In Proverbs&#8217; demythologized version, the protection comes not from supernatural beings but from the internalized virtues themselves: wisdom&#8217;s protection is wisdom functioning as a watchman within the person. The Christological application (Eph&#160;6:14&#8211;17 armor of God) is the later development of this protective-virtue tradition.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&#8220;Delivering you from the path of evil&#8221; (v12) introduces the first of two negative foils — the wicked man and the immoral woman — whose ways wisdom protects against. The literary structure of the &#8220;way&#8221; vocabulary is exhaustive in vv12&#8211;19: <i>derek</i> (way), <i>ʾōraḥ</i> (path), <i>nātîb</i> (bypath), <i>maʿgal</i> (track/rut). The density of path-language creates the effect of a moral landscape entirely mapped by wisdom&#8217;s geography. The evil man&#8217;s path is described in terms of speech (&#8220;twisted things&#8221;) before conduct — corrupt speech is the first marker of the deviant way.</p>",
        "13": "<p>&#8220;Abandoning the straight paths to walk in darkness&#8221; (v13) applies the light-and-dark moral imagery characteristic of Proverbs (4:18&#8211;19; 13:9) and the Psalms (Ps&#160;1:6; 119:105). The image likely draws on the practical experience of travel: a path walked in daylight is safe; the same path in darkness becomes dangerous. The moral life is mapped onto this physical reality: wisdom is the light by which the path of life can be safely walked. The wisdom tradition and the prophetic tradition (Isa&#160;8:20&#8211;22; 9:2; 42:16) share this light-of-guidance image.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Taking pleasure in evil&#8221; (v14) is the moral category the wisdom tradition finds most alarming: not the person who does evil despite themselves but the one who finds joy in it. The Psalms distinguish between those who sin inadvertently (<i>šᵉgāgôt</i>) and those who are &#8220;presumptuous&#8221; (<i>zēdîm</i>) in their sin (Ps&#160;19:12&#8211;13). Paul makes the same observation in Rom&#160;1:32: the worst level of moral corruption is not the sin itself but &#8220;not only doing these things but giving approval to those who practice them.&#8221;</p>",
        "15": "<p>The crooked and twisted paths of the wicked (v15) are defined by their fundamental contrast with the straight way of wisdom. &#8220;Twisted paths&#8221; (<i>nᵉlôzîm</i>) in the physical world are dangerous — one cannot travel them quickly or safely; one cannot know where they lead. The moral universe of Proverbs is spatially ordered: straight paths lead to life; twisted paths lead somewhere else. The figure of the wide and narrow ways in Matt&#160;7:13&#8211;14 draws on exactly this two-ways spatial moral imagery.</p>",
        "16": "<p>The &#8220;immoral woman / strange woman&#8221; (<i>ʾiššāh zārāh / nokrîyyāh</i>) in vv16&#8211;19 is the counterpart to Lady Wisdom in vv1&#8211;11. This structural juxtaposition — wise woman/foolish woman — is fully developed in ch9 (Wisdom&#8217;s feast vs. Folly&#8217;s feast). The origin of the figure is debated: she may be a real adulteress, a foreign cult prostitute associated with Canaanite religion, or a literary personification of the anti-wisdom way. Most likely she functions on multiple levels simultaneously — the literal adulteress, the symbol of covenant unfaithfulness, and the personification of every seductive alternative to wisdom.</p>",
        "17": "<p>&#8220;She has abandoned the partner of her youth and forgotten the covenant she made before God.&#8221; The marriage as a covenant witnessed by God (<i>bᵉrît ʾĕlōhîm</i>) is explicit in Mal&#160;2:14&#8211;16, where YHWH himself is said to have been &#8220;witness between you and the wife of your youth.&#8221; Proverbs&#8217; characterization of the adulterous woman as a covenant-breaker places marital fidelity within the theological framework of covenant — not merely a social contract but a relation in which God is the guardian. The link between marital unfaithfulness and covenant unfaithfulness to YHWH is developed at length in Hosea and Ezekiel.</p>",
        "18": "<p>The immoral woman&#8217;s house &#8220;leads down to death&#8221; and her paths &#8220;go to the shades (<i>rᵉpāʾîm</i>)&#8221; — Sheol imagery derived from the Canaanite underworld traditions that Israel inherited and transformed. The <i>rᵉpāʾîm</i> (shades of the dead) appear in Ugaritic texts as a class of divine beings; in Israel they become simply the weak, powerless dead in Sheol (Isa&#160;14:9; 26:14; Ps&#160;88:10). Proverbs uses this background to make the point viscerally: the house of adultery is a death-house, a portal to the underworld. What presents itself as erotic life leads to death.</p>",
        "19": "<p>&#8220;None who enter her house return; they never find their way back to the paths of life.&#8221; The finality and irreversibility of this statement is striking — Proverbs does not typically deal in absolute statements. The descent-without-return image echoes the ancient view of Sheol as a one-way journey (Job&#160;7:9&#8211;10; 10:21; 16:22). The warning is not that one cannot be forgiven but that certain paths, when entered, reshape the person in ways that make return practically impossible. The wisdom tradition is realistic about the ratchet-effect of moral habit.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The positive purpose clause (v20): &#8220;all this so that you will walk in the path of the good and stay on the road of the righteous.&#8221; The instruction against evil (vv12&#8211;19) serves the positive goal of the good life. This is the same positive-through-negative pedagogy of the Ten Commandments: the prohibitions (&#8220;you shall not&#8221;) serve the positive vision of a community of covenant faithfulness. Wisdom&#8217;s protection from the wicked and the adulterous is in service of the student&#8217;s flourishing in the covenant community.</p>",
        "21": "<p>&#8220;The righteous will live in the land&#8221; — the land-inheritance promise of the covenant (Deut&#160;11:8&#8211;9; 28:1&#8211;14) applied to the individual wisdom-keeper. Psalm&#160;37, the most wisdom-shaped of the Psalms, develops this promise extensively: the meek will inherit the land (Ps&#160;37:9, 11, 22, 29, 34) — a promise Jesus inherits and universalizes in Matt&#160;5:5. The wisdom tradition&#8217;s teaching about land-dwelling as the fruit of righteousness connects individual moral formation to the great covenant hope of a people at home in YHWH&#8217;s land.</p>",
        "22": "<p>&#8220;The wicked will be cut off from the land&#8221; inverts the covenant blessing: the covenant curse (Deut&#160;28:63&#8211;65) is exile from the land. Proverbs applies this covenant consequence to the individual moral sphere: the wicked are exiled from their place in the covenant community and its land. The vocabulary (<i>kārat</i> = cut off; <i>nāsaḥ</i> = uproot) is both legal-covenantal and agricultural — the wicked are removed like illegal occupants and uprooted like thorn bushes in a field. Chapter 2 ends with creation-level stakes: life in the land or removal from it.</p>"
    },
    "3": {
        "1": "<p>Chapter 3 opens a new instructional address (&#8220;my son&#8221;) focused on the practical implications of covenant relationship — trust, acknowledgment, honor, and discipline. The opening appeal not to &#8220;forget my instruction (<i>tôrātî</i>)&#8221; echoes the Deuteronomic charge not to forget the Torah (Deut&#160;4:9; 6:12; 8:11; Josh&#160;1:8). The father&#8217;s instruction participates in the same authority structure as the Mosaic Torah — not identical to it but continuous with it. This is the domestic-wisdom dimension of what Deuteronomy describes as national-covenant obligation.</p>",
        "2": "<p>&#8220;Long life, many years, and peace&#8221; as the outcome of keeping wisdom&#8217;s instruction replicates the covenant blessings of Deuteronomy (Deut&#160;5:33; 6:2; 30:16&#8211;20). The fifth commandment specifically promises long life to those who honor their parents (Exod&#160;20:12; Deut&#160;5:16); Proverbs extends the same promise to those who honor the teacher-father&#8217;s wisdom. The covenant logic is consistent: the life that aligns with the divine order flourishes; the life that defies it deteriorates.</p>",
        "3": "<p>&#8220;Let steadfast love (<i>ḥesed</i>) and faithfulness (<i>ʾĕmet</i>) never leave you; inscribe them on your heart.&#8221; This verse is directly connected to the Sinai covenant in Exod&#160;34:6&#8211;7, where YHWH reveals his character as &#8220;abounding in steadfast love and faithfulness (<i>rab-ḥesed wĕʾĕmet</i>).&#8221; The student is called to embody the divine character — to make the attributes of God their own interior disposition. The inscription &#8220;on the heart&#8221; anticipates Jer&#160;31:33 (the new covenant written on hearts rather than stone tablets), placing Proverbs&#8217; pedagogy within the arc of covenant promise.</p>",
        "4": "<p>&#8220;Favor and good reputation in the eyes of God and people&#8221; (v4) describes the social outcome of embodied covenant character. The formulation is strikingly parallel to what the narrator says about Samuel (1&#160;Sam&#160;2:26) and about Jesus (Luke&#160;2:52: &#8220;Jesus grew in wisdom and in stature and in favor with God and man&#8221;). Both Samuel and Jesus are presented as the ideal embodiment of covenant wisdom — the promised outcome of ch3&#8217;s instruction made personal in actual human lives.</p>",
        "5": "<p>&#8220;Trust in the LORD with all your heart&#8221; (v5) is among the most cited verses in all of Scripture. The command places the whole person (<i>bᵉkol-libbekā</i>) in the posture of covenantal trust rather than self-reliance. The Deuteronomic &#8220;love the LORD your God with all your heart, with all your soul, and with all your might&#8221; (Deut&#160;6:5) is the parent text; Prov&#160;3:5 is its wisdom application. Trust (<i>bāṭaḥ</i>) in Proverbs and the Psalms is the lived out reality of what covenant commitment looks like in practical decisions and daily dependence.</p>",
        "6": "<p>&#8220;Acknowledge him in everything you do, and he will direct your paths.&#8221; The Hebrew <i>dāʿēhû</i> (know him, acknowledge him) is covenantal knowledge — the relational knowing that implies loyalty and trust. This verse is the practical application of Deut&#160;6:4&#8211;9 (&#8220;you shall love the LORD... these words shall be on your heart... bind them... write them&#8221;) to daily life: every sphere of activity is to be brought under conscious acknowledgment of YHWH. The promise that God will &#8220;make straight your paths&#8221; has the resonance of Isa&#160;40:3 (&#8220;make straight in the desert a highway for our God&#8221;).</p>",
        "7": "<p>&#8220;Do not think of yourself as wise in your own eyes&#8221; (v7) targets the besetting sin of those who have received some wisdom — self-congratulation. Isaiah&#160;5:21 places &#8220;being wise in your own eyes&#8221; among the catalogue of serious covenant failures (alongside social injustice and intemperance). Proverbs returns to this theme repeatedly (11:2; 16:18; 26:12) because the danger of wisdom is that it can generate pride, which is the antithesis of the fear of the LORD on which wisdom rests. The sage must constantly return to the foundational disposition of humility before YHWH.</p>",
        "8": "<p>&#8220;This will bring health to your whole body and strength to your bones.&#8221; The physicality of wisdom&#8217;s blessing is characteristic of the Hebrew wisdom tradition, which does not separate spiritual and material flourishing. Greek wisdom tended toward the view that virtue was its own reward regardless of physical outcomes; Hebrew wisdom holds that the moral order is embedded in the physical creation, and that alignment with it produces physical flourishing as well as spiritual peace. The body is not separate from the moral sphere but embedded in it.</p>",
        "9": "<p>&#8220;Honor the LORD with your wealth and with the firstfruits (<i>rēʾšît</i>) of all you produce&#8221; (v9) grounds the instruction in the firstfruits legislation of the Mosaic code (Exod&#160;23:19; Lev&#160;23:10&#8211;14; Deut&#160;26:1&#8211;11). The firstfruits offering was Israel&#8217;s acknowledgment that the land and its produce belonged to YHWH — the first portion given back as the acknowledgment of the whole. Proverbs extends this principle beyond agricultural produce to all income: every form of wealth is to be first-acknowledged as God&#8217;s gift, with the first portion returned to him as a statement of that acknowledgment.</p>",
        "10": "<p>The agricultural blessing of overflowing barns and wine vats (v10) echoes the covenant prosperity promises of Deut&#160;28:8&#8211;12 and Mal&#160;3:10 (&#8220;bring the full tithe into the storehouse... and thereby put me to the test, says the LORD of hosts, if I will not open the windows of heaven for you and pour down for you a blessing until there is no more need&#8221;). This is not a health-and-wealth formula but a covenant principle: YHWH&#8217;s blessing of material provision is the response to honoring him with the firstfruits. The blessing presupposes covenant faithfulness as its condition.</p>",
        "11": "<p>&#8220;Do not reject the LORD&#8217;s discipline&#8221; (v11) applies the image of parental discipline (vv11&#8211;12) to YHWH&#8217;s dealings with his people. The identical point is made at the national level in Deut&#160;8:5 (&#8220;as a man disciplines his son, the LORD your God disciplines you&#8221;) and in the historical books (1&#160;Kgs&#160;12:11; cf. Amos&#160;4:6&#8211;11 where divine judgments are listed as the discipline Israel refused). The wisdom application is personal: the hardships of an individual life are not evidence of divine absence or hostility but of divine paternal engagement.</p>",
        "12": "<p>&#8220;The LORD corrects those he loves, as a father the son he delights in&#8221; (v12) is directly quoted in Heb&#160;12:5&#8211;6 as the theological rationale for the community&#8217;s endurance of suffering. The author of Hebrews explicitly identifies this as &#8220;a word of encouragement that addresses you as sons&#8221; — the wisdom pedagogy of Proverbs becomes the hermeneutical key for understanding Christian suffering. The Proverbs verse itself draws on the Deuteronomic father-son covenant framework and will be applied in the NT to God&#8217;s relationship with believers in Christ.</p>",
        "13": "<p>The &#8220;blessed is the person who finds wisdom&#8221; (<i>ʾašrê</i> beatitude) in v13 participates in a wisdom-beatitude tradition that runs from Pss&#160;1:1; 2:12; 32:1&#8211;2; 34:8 through the Sermon on the Mount (Matt&#160;5:3&#8211;11). The beatitude form is not a general observation about cause-and-effect but a declaration of the blessed state that already characterizes the wisdom-possessor. It is closer to a proclamation than a promise — wisdom-finding is itself the blessed state, not merely the means to it.</p>",
        "14": "<p>&#8220;Her return is better than the return on silver, and her profit better than fine gold&#8221; (v14) uses the commercial language of the market to commend wisdom to a culture where commercial wisdom was highly valued. The use of trade vocabulary (<i>sāḥar</i>, commerce; <i>tᵉbûʾāh</i>, profit) is not a concession to materialism but a rhetorical move that meets the student where they live: in an economy where calculating returns is a daily necessity, the highest possible return is wisdom itself. The Instruction of Amenemope uses similar economic comparisons to recommend the virtuous life.</p>",
        "15": "<p>&#8220;Nothing you could want measures up to her&#8221; (v15) places wisdom in the category of the incomparable — the same superlative used of YHWH himself (Exod&#160;15:11; Ps&#160;86:8; 89:6). The rhetorical escalation of values — silver, gold, rubies, &#8220;nothing you could want&#8221; — exhausts the human category of desire to make the point that wisdom transcends even the most coveted goods. The verse is a practical call to redirect human desire from its natural objects toward wisdom as the most desire-worthy of all goods.</p>",
        "16": "<p>&#8220;In her right hand is long life; in her left hand are wealth and honor&#8221; (v16) — wisdom as a figure holding gifts in both hands is a visual anthropomorphism. In Egyptian iconography, the goddess Ma&#8217;at is depicted holding symbols of life and order; in Mesopotamian art, divine figures present gifts to humans. Whether Proverbs is directly drawing on these traditions or developing an independent image is debated; either way, the personification of wisdom as a gift-bearing figure places Proverbs in the international wisdom tradition while insisting that wisdom&#8217;s gifts ultimately come from YHWH.</p>",
        "17": "<p>&#8220;Her ways are pleasant and all her paths lead to peace (<i>šālôm</i>)&#8221; (v17) presents wisdom&#8217;s road as intrinsically enjoyable. This contrasts with the common view that virtue is achieved only through painful effort. The wisdom tradition acknowledges that discipline and instruction involve hardship (3:11&#8211;12) but insists that the fundamental character of wisdom&#8217;s way is pleasantness (<i>nōʿam</i>) and peace (<i>šālôm</i>). <i>Šālôm</i> (comprehensive wellbeing — not merely absence of conflict but positive flourishing) is the covenant term for the totality of blessing that right relationship with YHWH produces.</p>",
        "18": "<p>&#8220;She is a tree of life (<i>ʿēṣ ḥayyîm</i>) to those who grasp her&#8221; (v18) applies the Eden symbol to wisdom. The tree of life (Gen&#160;2:9; 3:22&#8211;24) represented access to immortality — what was forfeited in the fall. Proverbs does not restore Eden literally but applies the image to wisdom: to grasp wisdom is to have access to the kind of life that the tree symbolized. The image of wisdom as the tree of life recurs in 11:30 (the righteous&#8217; fruit is a tree of life) and 13:12; 15:4. The Book of Revelation finally literalizes the symbol in the new Jerusalem (Rev&#160;22:2) — the consummation toward which all the tree-of-life references point.</p>",
        "19": "<p>&#8220;By wisdom the LORD laid the foundation of the earth&#8221; (v19) grounds the student&#8217;s wisdom-pursuit in the cosmic fact that wisdom was the instrument of creation. This cosmological claim is developed extensively in 8:22&#8211;31, where Wisdom is present at creation as YHWH&#8217;s master craftsman. Psalm&#160;104:24 (&#8220;in wisdom you have made them all&#8221;) and Job&#160;28:23&#8211;27 (God understands wisdom&#8217;s way and used it to establish creation) stand in the same tradition. To pursue wisdom is not merely to acquire a useful skill but to align oneself with the principle by which the universe was made.</p>",
        "20": "<p>The creation-wisdom passage (vv19&#8211;20) grounds the invitation to wisdom in cosmology: the same wisdom that separated the waters and released the dew is the wisdom being offered to the student. The deep waters (<i>tᵉhōmôt</i>) recall Gen&#160;1:2 and the primeval waters of chaos that God ordered. Proverbs&#8217; implicit claim is that the moral order of human life is continuous with the physical order of creation: wisdom&#8217;s instruction is not an arbitrary set of rules but a description of the way the world actually works at its deepest level.</p>",
        "21": "<p>&#8220;My son, keep these in view&#8221; resumes the direct address after the cosmological aside of vv19&#8211;20. The sequence is pedagogically significant: the cosmological grounding precedes the practical instruction. By first establishing that wisdom is the foundation of the created order, the teacher gives the student a reason to take the practical instruction seriously. The wisdom that governs their daily choices is the same wisdom that governs the movements of the deep waters and the clouds. The instruction is not arbitrary but aligned with the deepest structure of reality.</p>",
        "22": "<p>&#8220;They will bring life to your soul and beauty to your neck&#8221; — the jewelry-and-life pairing (cf. 1:9; 3:3) presents wisdom&#8217;s gifts as both inward (life, <i>nepeš</i>) and outward (beauty, honor). The wisdom tradition consistently holds together the inner and outer dimensions of flourishing: genuine wisdom produces both internal wellbeing and external social honor. The Greek tendency to separate the private virtue of the soul from the public recognition of the community is absent from the Hebrew wisdom tradition, which expects the two to align in a well-ordered covenant community.</p>",
        "23": "<p>&#8220;You will go on your way in security, without stumbling.&#8221; The secured journey is the fruit of internalized wisdom. Psalm&#160;91 (&#8220;he will command his angels... they will bear you up, lest you strike your foot against a stone&#8221;) promises the same protection in terms of divine guardianship; Prov&#160;3:23&#8211;24 grounds the same security in wisdom as the guardian. The two are not in tension: God&#8217;s protection comes through wisdom as its instrument.</p>",
        "24": "<p>&#8220;When you lie down, you will not be afraid; your sleep will be peaceful.&#8221; The gift of untroubled sleep is a recurring sign of divine blessing and security (Ps&#160;4:8; Lev&#160;26:6; Job&#160;11:18&#8211;19). The anxiety that disrupts sleep is characteristic of those who depend on their own resources — the wicked whose strategies might fail overnight. The wisdom-keeper who trusts in YHWH (v5) can sleep without the monitoring anxiety of the self-reliant, because their security rests in something more stable than their own vigilance.</p>",
        "25": "<p>&#8220;Do not fear sudden catastrophe (<i>paḥad pittʾōm</i>)&#8221; echoes the language of Job&#160;22:10 (&#8220;snares are all around you, and sudden terror overwhelms you&#8221;) and the protective promises of Ps&#160;91:5&#8211;6. The paranoia of the wicked — always fearing the sudden reversal that will expose them — is absent from the wisdom-keeper. This is one of wisdom&#8217;s practical gifts: freedom from the low-grade anxiety that dogs those whose security rests on precarious foundations (wealth, reputation, power).</p>",
        "26": "<p>&#8220;The LORD will be your confidence (<i>kislᵉkā</i>)&#8221; — the translation &#8220;confidence&#8221; renders a difficult word that may mean the side/hip (as a place of confidence) or simply trust/confidence itself. The verse places YHWH as the ground of security rather than any human resource. This is the practical application of Ps&#160;62:5&#8211;8 (&#8220;for God alone, O my soul, wait in silence, for my hope is from him... trust in him at all times, O people&#8221;). Wisdom&#8217;s instruction shapes people who know where to place their confidence and where not to.</p>",
        "27": "<p>&#8220;Do not withhold good from those who deserve it&#8221; (v27) introduces the neighbor-ethics section (vv27&#8211;30). These verses are the practical social expression of the covenant character (ḥesed-wĕʾemet, v3) that the student has been invited to embody. The social obligations — giving when you can, not deferring, not plotting against neighbors, not quarreling without cause — are the horizontal dimensions of the vertical covenant relationship described in vv1&#8211;26. Covenant life with YHWH is expressed through covenant-shaped life with neighbors.</p>",
        "28": "<p>&#8220;Do not say, &#8216;Come back tomorrow,&#8217; when you can help now.&#8221; The deferral-of-good is a specific form of withholding that the wisdom tradition targets because it preserves the appearance of eventual generosity while denying the actual need. James&#160;2:15&#8211;16 applies exactly this scenario: &#8220;if a brother or sister is poorly clothed and lacking in daily food, and one of you says to them, &#8216;go in peace, be warmed and filled,&#8217; without giving them the things needed for the body, what good is that?&#8221; The NT application is continuous with the OT wisdom teaching.</p>",
        "29": "<p>&#8220;Do not plot harm against your neighbor who lives beside you in trust&#8221; (v29). The word &#8220;trust (<i>lābeṭaḥ</i>)&#8221; — the same root as &#8220;trust in the LORD&#8221; in v5 — creates a quiet resonance: the neighbor trusts in their neighbor as one expression of the broader covenant trust. To betray a neighbor&#8217;s trust is to participate in the erosion of the social fabric that covenant community requires. Micah&#160;7:5&#8211;6 describes the collapse of covenant community in exactly these terms: &#8220;put no trust in a neighbor... for the son treats the father with contempt.&#8221;</p>",
        "30": "<p>&#8220;Do not quarrel without cause&#8221; (v30) reflects the wisdom tradition&#8217;s consistent concern with the destruction of social peace through needless conflict. The legal register (<i>rîb</i>, quarrel/lawsuit) suggests that Proverbs has courtroom as well as street conflict in mind. The Psalms repeatedly describe the wicked as those who attack the innocent &#8220;without cause (<i>ḥinnām</i>)&#8221; (Ps&#160;7:4; 35:7; 69:4); wisdom&#8217;s instruction is to remove oneself from that pattern entirely. Unnecessary conflict destroys the community that wisdom is trying to build.</p>",
        "31": "<p>&#8220;Do not envy the violent person&#8221; (v31) addresses the temptation to admire the apparently successful wicked. Psalm&#160;37 and Ps&#160;73 both wrestle at length with the problem of the prospering wicked — the psalmist&#8217;s temptation to &#8220;envy the arrogant&#8221; when they see the wicked flourish (Ps&#160;73:3). Proverbs&#8217; advice is practical: do not even orient your desire toward the violent person&#8217;s path. The wisdom tradition knows that what we envy shapes what we become; to envy the violent is to begin the journey toward violence.</p>",
        "32": "<p>&#8220;The LORD detests the devious but the upright are in his confidence (<i>sôdô</i>)&#8221; — the divine council (<i>sôd</i>, the intimate inner circle; cf. Ps&#160;25:14; Jer&#160;23:18; Amos&#160;3:7) is the community of those admitted to YHWH&#8217;s intimate counsel. The prophets claim access to this divine council; Proverbs democratizes the claim: the upright person who lives wisely in YHWH&#8217;s world is admitted to the inner circle of divine intimacy. This is the relational goal of all wisdom&#8217;s instruction — not mere moral uprightness but friendship with God.</p>",
        "33": "<p>&#8220;The LORD&#8217;s curse on the house of the wicked, blessing on the home of the righteous&#8221; (v33) applies the Deuteronomic covenant blessings and curses (Deut&#160;28:15&#8211;20 for the curse; 28:3&#8211;8 for the blessing) to the household. The individual wisdom-teacher&#8217;s instruction participates in the same theological world as Deuteronomy&#8217;s national covenant: wise living brings divine blessing on the household; wicked living brings divine curse. This is not mechanical but covenantal: the blessed household is the one in which YHWH&#8217;s character is being embodied.</p>",
        "34": "<p>&#8220;He mocks the mockers but shows grace (<i>ḥēn</i>) to the humble (<i>ʿᵃnāwîm</i>)&#8221; (v34) is one of the most widely quoted proverbs in the NT. James&#160;4:6 and 1&#160;Pet&#160;5:5 both cite this verse (from the LXX) in their teaching on humility before God. The verse is the precise verbal foundation for the gospel&#8217;s central claim about grace: God gives grace not to the self-sufficient and proud but to those who have been brought low. The NT deployment of this verse represents the kind of continuous wisdom-appropriation that confirms Proverbs&#8217; ongoing canonical authority.</p>",
        "35": "<p>&#8220;The wise will inherit honor, but fools are left with disgrace.&#8221; The closing verse seals the chapter with the ultimate social outcomes of wisdom and folly: honor (<i>kābôd</i>) and shame (<i>qālôn</i>). In the honor-shame culture of the ancient Mediterranean world, these were not merely psychological states but social realities determining one&#8217;s standing in the community. The wisdom tradition consistently presents its instruction as the path to genuine, enduring honor — not the false honor of wealth or power but the deep honor that comes from a life well-lived in alignment with the divine order. Chapter 3 closes the first major instructional movement of the book with this vision of wisdom&#8217;s ultimate reward.</p>"
    }
}

existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
merge_comm(existing, new_data)
save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)

for ch in sorted(new_data.keys(), key=int):
    vv = new_data[ch]
    have = sum(1 for v in vv if v in existing.get(ch, {}))
    print(f'  ch{ch}: {have}/{len(vv)} verses present')
